    "summary": "In July 2019, a Mineola school district employee downloaded the Ryuk ransomware via a phishing email, triggering the same wave of attacks that hit neighboring Rockville Centre. No ransom was demanded and none was paid because the district's backup servers happened to be offline for maintenance, leaving them unencrypted and fully recoverable. The incident became a widely cited example of how offline backups prevented a ransom payout.",
    "source_name": "NBC New York",
    "source_url": "https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/long-island-schools-hacked-district-forced-to-pay-88000-in-ransom/1491924/",
    "date": "2019-07-25",
    "severity": "medium",
    "featured": false,
    "industry": "SLED",
    "enriched_summary": "Mineola School District was infected by Ryuk ransomware in early August 2019 — the same wave that hit neighboring Rockville Centre — after an employee downloaded the malware via a phishing email. Ryuk is specifically designed to encrypt backup systems in addition to primary data; however, the district's backup servers happened to be taken offline for summer maintenance, leaving them disconnected and unencrypted. This inadvertent isolation of backups enabled full network recovery without ransom payment, in contrast to Rockville Centre's $88,000 payout.",
