    "enriched_summary": "SamSam ransomware struck CDOT on February 21, 2018, targeting Windows-based back-office systems across all 200 CDOT locations statewide while leaving traffic control and highway cameras operational. The malware re-infected systems with a mutated variant during initial recovery efforts, requiring up to 150 simultaneous workers — including state IT staff, cybersecurity consultants, and federal agencies — to remediate 1,274 laptops, 427 desktops, 339 servers, 158 databases, 154 software applications, and all VoIP phones. Governor Hickenlooper declared the first governor-declared cyber emergency in U.S. history on March 1; the state refused the bitcoin ransom demand and relied on a pre-existing data segmentation backup strategy called 'Backup Colorado.'",
