    "healthcare_sector": "Home Health",
    "sled_sector": null,
    "industry": "Healthcare",
    "featured": false,
    "enriched_summary": "On September 26, 2025, cybersecurity researcher Jeremiah Fowler discovered a publicly accessible, unencrypted, password-free 23.7 GB database belonging to Archer Health Inc., a home health and palliative care provider based in Carlsbad, California. The exposed database contained approximately 145,596 files — including PDFs, PNGs, and other image formats — with full patient records including Social Security numbers, discharge summaries, home health certifications, and care plan documents. The database was secured within hours of Fowler's notification, but it was not possible to determine how long it had been exposed or whether criminals had already accessed or copied the data. Archer Health subsequently reported the incident to HHS OCR as affecting 4,285 individuals.",
