    "healthcare_sector": "Health Plan / Integrated Delivery System",
    "sled_sector": null,
    "industry": "Healthcare",
    "featured": true,
    "enriched_summary": "Kaiser Permanente disclosed in April 2024 that third-party tracking code embedded in its websites, patient portals, and mobile applications had been transmitting protected health information to Google, Microsoft, Meta, and Twitter/X without member consent from November 2017 through May 2024 — a period of over six years. The tracking technologies captured names, IP addresses, sign-in statuses, health encyclopedia search terms (symptoms, conditions, medications), and navigation patterns on authenticated pages. Kaiser discovered the issue through a voluntary internal investigation, severed the connections, and reported the breach to HHS OCR as affecting up to 13.4 million current and former members — the second-largest healthcare data breach disclosed in 2024. Kaiser agreed to a $46 million settlement (potentially increasing to $47.5 million under certain conditions), with individual member payouts estimated at $20-$40.",
