    "healthcare_sector": "Behavioral Health",
    "sled_sector": null,
    "industry": "Healthcare",
    "featured": false,
    "enriched_summary": "In February 2024, the Hunters International ransomware group attacked Omni Family Health, a California nonprofit operating approximately 40 community health centers across the Central Valley including Kern, Kings, Tulare, and Fresno counties. The attack caused a five-day IT outage before being discovered on August 7, 2024 when Hunters International listed the organization on its dark web leak site, claiming to have stolen 2.7 terabytes of data — which was published on August 23, 2024. Approximately 468,344 patients and employees had records exposed, including names, Social Security numbers, and medical information. Omni Family Health agreed to a $6.5 million class action settlement, with roughly $2.2 million allocated to attorneys' fees and the remainder compensating class members with up to $5,000 each for documented losses.",
