    "title": "Kaiser Permanente: $47.5M Class Action Settlement for Web Tracker PHI Disclosure Reaches Final Approval Stage",
    "summary": "Kaiser Permanente agreed to pay up to $47.5 million to settle class action litigation over its use of tracking pixels and web analytics tools (Google, Microsoft, Meta, X/Twitter) on its websites, patient portals, and mobile applications, which shared member names, IP addresses, medical search queries, and internal communications without consent from approximately 13.4 million members. The settlement — covering California and eight other states for activity between November 2017 and May 2024 — received preliminary court approval in December 2025. The final fairness hearing is scheduled for April 30–May 7, 2026, with a claims deadline of March 12, 2026. Individual payouts are estimated at $20–$42.",
