    "title": "Blue Shield of California: 4.7 Million Members' PHI Shared with Google Ads via Misconfigured Analytics",
    "summary": "On April 9, 2025, Blue Shield of California disclosed that a misconfigured Google Analytics integration on its member-facing websites had allowed protected health information to be transmitted to Google's advertising platform (Google Ads) from April 2021 through January 2024. Approximately 4.7 million members were affected — ranking it among the largest healthcare data breaches reported to HHS OCR in 2025. Exposed data included insurance plan names and group numbers, member gender, family size, zip code, medical claim service dates and providers, Blue Shield account identifiers, and Find-a-Doctor search queries. Blue Shield severed the Google Analytics connection in January 2024 but only discovered the full scope of the exposure on February 11, 2025. Multiple class action lawsuits were filed and an OCR investigation is expected given the impermissible use of PHI for advertising purposes.",
    "source_url": "https://therecord.media/healthcare-data-breaches-blue-shield-california",
    "source_name": "The Record / HIPAA Journal",
    "date": "2025-04-09",
    "severity": "critical",
    "state": "CA",
    "org_type": "Health Plan / PBM (Pharmacy Benefit)",
    "healthcare_sector": "Health Insurance / Pharmacy Benefit",
    "sled_sector": null,
    "industry": "Healthcare",
    "featured": true,
    "enriched_summary": "From April 2021 through January 2024, Blue Shield of California had a misconfigured Google Analytics integration on its member-facing websites that allowed protected health information to be transmitted to Google's advertising platform (Google Ads). The misconfiguration was fixed in January 2024, but Blue Shield did not discover the full scope of the exposure until February 11, 2025, and did not publicly disclose the incident until April 9, 2025. Approximately 4.7 million members were affected, with exposed data including insurance plan names, group numbers, member gender, family size, zip codes, medical claim service dates and providers, Blue Shield account identifiers, and Find-a-Doctor search queries. Blue Shield stated no bad actor was involved and that Google had not used the information for purposes other than advertising, but the incident ranks among the largest healthcare data breaches reported to HHS OCR in 2025 and reflects escalating FTC and HHS scrutiny of healthcare organizations using third-party tracking technologies.",
