    "summary": "American Associated Pharmacies, a member-owned cooperative supporting over 2,000 independent U.S. pharmacies including California members, suffered an Embargo ransomware attack that began October 13, 2024. The attackers allegedly stole 1.469 TB of data and demanded $1.3 million ransom (reportedly paid), then demanded a second $1.3 million payment for deletion of stolen data. AAP issued formal breach notification letters beginning November 11, 2025, covering California, Maine, Vermont, and Washington residents. Exposed data potentially included names, addresses, dates of birth, Social Security numbers, passport/driver's license numbers, bank account numbers, medical and clinical treatment details, provider names, prescription data, health insurance information, and usernames/passwords. Multiple class action lawsuits were filed in California and other states.",
