    "enriched_summary": "On June 6, 2024, the RansomHub ransomware group compromised Rite Aid's computer systems, exfiltrating customer data for approximately 2.2 million individuals who made retail pharmacy purchases between June 6, 2017, and July 30, 2017. The breach was identified within 12 hours but not in time to prevent data theft. Rite Aid operated approximately 95 Washington state locations and 39 Bartell Drugs stores (a Seattle-founded chain acquired by Rite Aid in 2020), making Washington one of the states with the highest customer exposure. Stolen data included names, addresses, dates of birth, and driver's license or government ID numbers. Rite Aid — already operating under bankruptcy proceedings — agreed to pay $6.8 million to settle class action litigation, with class members eligible for claims up to $10,000 for documented losses.",
